Lab 3A

Logistic regression and LDA

2021

In this lab you train models to classify emails as either spam or non-spam based 57 features of the email. The data set for this lab is spam from the package kernlab. The variable type contains the classifications.

Data exploration

  1. Load the package kernlab and load the spam in workspace with the function data(). Check its help file for the description of the data.
library(kernlab)
data("spam")
  1. Display the boxplots of the standardized features (so exclude type). What does these plots tell you about the distributions of the features?
boxplot(scale(spam[, -58]), cex = .3, las = 2)

  1. To avoid outliers, cut the scores of all 57 features into 4 approximately equal parts. Save the new data set as spam4.
spam4 <- spam %>% 
  mutate(across(1:57, ntile, 4))

Data partitioning

We first make a vector to partition the data in a training set consisting of 75% of the data, and a test of 25% of the data.

  1. Set the seed to 10 for reproducibility, and make the vector train consisting of 75% of the row numbers with the function createDataPartition().
set.seed(10) 
train <- createDataPartition(y = spam4$type, p = .75, list = FALSE)

Model training

We first train the three logistic regression models (one without and two with regularization), and the two (linear and quadratic) discriminant models.

Logistic regression

  1. Fit the logistic regression model with all 57 features to the training set, and save the object as train_glm.
train_glm <- glm(type ~ . , family = "binomial", data = spam4[train, ])
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred

The warning glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred implies that one or more features have extreme parameter estimates and standard errors.

Lasso and ridge regression

Shrinkage avoids extremely large parameter estimates. The function glmnet() performs both lasso and ridge regression.

  1. Train the logistic regression model with the lasso and the ridge. Do not forget that argument x requires a matrix as input, and to set the familiy to "binomial". Save the objects as train_lasso and train_ridge.
train_lasso <- glmnet(x = as.matrix(spam4[train, -58]), 
                      y = spam4[train, 58], 
                      family = "binomial")

train_ridge <- glmnet(x = as.matrix(spam4[train, -58]), 
                      y = spam4[train, 58], 
                      family = "binomial", 
                      alpha = 0)
  1. Plot both objects with the arguments label = TRUE and xvar = "lambda". Which coefficients are most affected by the shrinkage.
plot(train_lasso, label = TRUE, xvar="lambda")

plot(train_ridge, label = TRUE, xvar="lambda")

  1. Perform a 5-fold cross-validation to determine the optimal value for the shrinkage parameters lambda with cv.glmnet(). Save the objects as train_cv.lasso and train_cv.ridge.
set.seed(1)
train_cv.lasso <- cv.glmnet(x = as.matrix(spam4[train, -58]), 
                            y = spam4[train, 58], 
                            family = "binomial",
                            nfolds = 5)
train_cv.ridge <- cv.glmnet(x = as.matrix(spam4[train, -58]), 
                            y = spam4[train, 58], 
                            family = "binomial",
                            nfolds = 5,
                            alpha = 0)
  1. Plot the objects train_cv.lasso and train_cv.lasso, and interpret the plots.
plot(train_cv.lasso)

plot(train_cv.ridge)

  1. Display the parameter estimates of train_glm, spam.cv.lasso and spam.cv.ridge side-by-side with the function cbind(), rounded to two decimals.
round(

LDA

  1. Perform a linear and quadratic discriminant analysis on the spam4 data. Save the fitted objects under an appropriate name (e.g. train_lda and train_qda).
train_lda <- lda(x = spam4[train, -58], grouping = spam4[train, 58])
train_qda <- qda(x = spam4[train, -58], grouping = spam4[train, 58])

Model testing

It is time to compare the performance of the three logistic models and the two discriminant analyses on the test set.

  1. Save the predictions of these models on the test set with the function predict(). Check the help files for predict.glm, predict.lda and predict.qda for the arguments. Save the objects under appropriate names (e.g. pred_glm, pred_lasso, etc.).
pred_glm    <- predict(train_glm, 
                            newdata = spam4[-train, -58], 
                             type = "response")

pred_lasso  <- predict(train_cv.lasso, 
                            newx = as.matrix(spam4[-train, -58]), 
                            type = "response") 

pred_ridge  <- predict(train_cv.ridge, 
                            newx = as.matrix(spam4[-train, -58]), 
                            type = "response") 


pred_lda    <- predict(train_lda, spam4[-train, -58])

pred_qda    <- predict(train_qda, spam4[-train, -58])
  1. Check the content of the predicted objects, and either compute or extract the factor with the predicted classifications “nospam” and “spam”. Save these factors under appropriate names (e.g. class_glm, class_lasso, etc.).
class_glm   <- factor(pred_glm > .5, 
                         labels = c("nonspam", "spam"))

class_lasso <- factor(pred_lasso > 0.5, 
                             labels = c("nonspam", "spam"))

class_ridge <- factor(pred_ridge > 0.5, 
                             labels = c("nonspam", "spam"))

class_lda   <- pred_lda$class

class_qda   <- pred_qda$class
  1. Display the confusion matrices of the five models, and save them under appropriate names.

  1. Compute and display the misclassification test error rates of the five models.
miscl <- function(x) 1 - sum(diag(x)) / sum(x)

data.frame(glm   = miscl(conf_glm),
           lasso = miscl(conf_lasso),
           ridge = miscl(conf_ridge),
           lda   = miscl(conf_lda),
           qda   = miscl(conf_qda)) %>% 
  round(4)

  1. In one figure, display and interpret the ROC curves (in different colors) for the predicted probabilities of

    • the random variable runif(1150)

    • the lasso model

    • the QDA.

plot(roc(spam4[-train, 58], runif(1150)))
plot(roc(spam4[-train, 58], pred_glm), add = T, col="blue")
plot(roc(spam4[-train, 58], pred_qda$posterior[, 2]), add = T, col="red")
